            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> See `nvim --clean file:///test +ls!`.\n\nI don't quite understand what the issue being raised here is. Based on my understanding, our current pattern is to open the argument if it is a file; otherwise, it is treated as the name for an empty buffer, which allows for configuration via `BufReadCmd`. This doesn't seem like a random design; to me, it looks like a very clean API convention—always using `BufReadCmd` to customize how certain links are opened.\n\nIt is possible to handle `file://` directly by modifying `path.c`, but it seems unnecessary since there are other types of links we need to open as well. If there is an issue with `BufReadCmd`, I think it would be better to fix that issue rather than creating alternative implementation methods.\n\nImplementing this in the cleanest way in C would result in re-implementing the logic we already have in `vim.uri` within the C code. I believe this is why #38006 chose to do it this way.\n\n",
