            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I don't quite understand what the issue being raised here is. Based on my understanding, our current pattern is **to open the argument if it is a file**; otherwise, it is treated as the name for an empty buffer, which allows for configuration via `BufReadCmd`.\n\nYou are correct that `BufReadCmd` works for most URIs that netrw handles: `scp://` URIs open in a buffer starting with `scp://*`, `ftp://` URIs open in a buffer starting with `ftp://*`, etc. This pattern works for all non-`file://` URIs. However....\n\n`file://` is different in that `file://` URIs do not open in a buffer starting with `file://*`, but instead opens in the buffer corresponding to the file that it represents. This doesn't work with `BufReadCmd`, because once a `BufReadCmd` autocommand is run. the `file://*` buffer will have already been created. So it needs to sloppily delete the buffer, which is hacky (`:bd` doesn't completely remove the buffer, and even if it was changed to use `:bw`, it would still increment the buffer number).\n\nNotice how in the code for netrw, `file://` is handled separately from all other URIs:\n\n```vimscript\n\" plugin/netrwPlugin.vim:40-41\n    au BufReadCmd file://* call netrw#FileUrlEdit(expand(\"<amatch>\"))\n    au BufReadCmd ftp://*,rcp://*,scp://*,dav://*,davs://*,rsync://*,sftp://* exe \"sil doau BufReadPre \".fnameescape(expand(\"<amatch>\"))|call netrw#Nread(2,expand(\"<amatch>\"))|exe \"sil doau BufReadPost \".fnameescape(expand(\"<amatch>\"))\n```\n\n> It is possible to handle `file://` directly by modifying `path.c`, but it seems unnecessary since there are other types of links we need to open as well.\n\nIn summary, `file://` should be handled in `path.c`, while all other URIs should be in a plugin using `BufReadCmd` (probably `runtime/plugin/net.lua`).",
