        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Maybe I'm not understanding the use case correctly here, but _why_ do we want to special-case `file:///` and even add support in path.c? Curl can handle reading these files. Writing is not supported, but this can be easily special-cased from the `BufWriteCmd`.\n\nThe issue mentioned above is that `BufReadCmd` will open a buffer for the corresponding file after opening a `file://` buffer, and then delete the `file://` buffer. This implementation makes it seem less than perfect, but I believe we can proceed with this approach for now.\n\n> I haven't seen a good point on why we want to resolve `file:///` URIs to their actual file. To me, `file:///tmp/a` and `/tmp/a` are two different things, even if they point to the same entity. E.g. `scp://localhost:/tmp/a` also points to `/tmp/a`. Do we want to special case that too?\n\nMy understanding of this is that different links like `scp` or `https` need to go through an \"adapter\" before being handled by nvim, so we don't need to worry about cases like `scp://localhost`. However, in the case of `file://`, nvim itself acts as the adapter, so we need to provide more comprehensive support.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-28T11:49:01Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39278#issuecomment-4334930267",
